---
import SiteLayout from '../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

const groups = [
  {
    title: 'Environment',
    items: ['Setup Cunzhi', 'Install Cunzhi', 'Check Cunzhi Status'],
  },
  {
    title: 'Settings and setup snippets',
    items: ['Open Cunzhi Settings', 'Show Cunzhi MCP Config', 'Show Cunzhi Prompt Workflow'],
  },
];
---

<SiteLayout title="Commands | Cunzhi" description="Command surface for the Cunzhi Cursor plugin.">
  <article class="doc-article">
    <p class="eyebrow">Commands</p>
    <h1>First release command set</h1>
    <p>
      The plugin keeps the command surface narrow on purpose. Every command either validates the local binaries or
      helps the user move through the upstream Cunzhi setup flow without leaving Cursor.
    </p>

    {groups.map((group) => (
      <section class="command-group">
        <h2>{group.title}</h2>
        <ul class="command-list">
          {group.items.map((item) => (
            <li>{item}</li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </section>
    ))}

    <h2>Wrapper behavior</h2>
    <p>
      Commands rely on <code>node scripts/ensure-cunzhi.mjs</code>, <code>node scripts/setup-cunzhi.mjs</code>, and
      <code>node scripts/run-cunzhi.mjs</code> so missing binaries, install guidance, and settings launch behavior all
      come back as stable JSON.
    </p>
  </article>
</SiteLayout>
